## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Impact |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Fatal at runtime |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** | Dead code — cleanup never runs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | Fatal at runtime |
| `volatile bool` for signaling | Works but not cancellation-aware | Can't unblock waiting calls |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            bool itemAcquired = false;
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                itemAcquired = true;
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — roll back partial work
                if (itemAcquired)
                    RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerTask is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel();

        // Wait for graceful exit with a timeout (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        var effectiveTimeout = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(effectiveTimeout)) != _workerTask)
        {
            // Log warning: worker didn't stop in time.
            // In .NET 8 there is NO forced termination equivalent.
        }

        // Observe any exceptions so they don't go unhandled
        try { await _workerTask; }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { /* expected */ }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        try { _workerTask?.GetAwaiter().GetResult(); }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. `Thread.Abort()` silently becomes a runtime bomb**
It compiles fine but throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime. There is **no equivalent** — you must use cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

**2. Blocking calls won't unblock with `volatile bool`**
If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., `BlockingCollection.Take()`), setting a bool won't wake it. Pass a `CancellationToken` to the blocking API so cancellation interrupts the wait:
```csharp
// Before: blocks forever, ignores _running flag
var item = queue.Take();

// After: throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
var item = queue.Take(token);
```

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` becomes dead code**
This exception is never thrown in .NET 8. Your rollback logic **silently stops executing**. Replace with `catch (OperationCanceledException)`.

**4. `Thread.ResetAbort()` — no equivalent needed**
`OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception — it doesn't auto-rethrow like `ThreadAbortException` did, so no "reset" is necessary.

**5. No forced termination fallback**
In Framework, `Abort()` was the last resort. In .NET 8, if your worker ignores the token, it hangs. **Every blocking call in the pipeline must accept a `CancellationToken`** — audit `GetNextItem`, `ProcessItem`, and any I/O they call.
